<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="366" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,764,1879,1973]" lastBlockId="7.[809,1421,178,476]" pageId="7" pageNumber="366">
Five specimens of this rarely recorded species were captured in forested habitats on the Liberian side of the mountain between 
<quantity box="[522,600,1947,1973]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.8" pageId="7" pageNumber="366" unit="m" value="780.0">780 m</quantity>
and 
<quantity box="[664,764,1947,1973]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="7" pageNumber="366" unit="m" value="1200.0">1,200 m</quantity>
a.s.l. A single roost was discovered in an old mine adit at Mt Tokadeh, adjacent to Mt 
<collectingRegion box="[1253,1333,212,238]" country="Liberia" name="Nimba" pageId="7" pageNumber="366">Nimba</collectingRegion>
on the Liberian side. This species was previously recorded from Liberian 
<collectingRegion box="[999,1078,280,306]" country="Liberia" name="Nimba" pageId="7" pageNumber="366">Nimba</collectingRegion>
by Verschuren (1977) [as 
<taxonomicName box="[809,932,314,340]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="366" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alcyone">
<emphasis box="[809,932,314,340]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="366">R. alcyone</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
], and Wolton 
<emphasis box="[1096,1146,314,340]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="366">et al</emphasis>
. (1982) [as 
<taxonomicName box="[1285,1412,314,340]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="366" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="clivosus">
<emphasis box="[1285,1412,314,340]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="366">R. clivosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
] (see 
<bibRefCitation author="FAHR, J. &amp; B. A. DJOSSA &amp; H. VIERHAUS" box="[869,1083,348,374]" pageId="7" pageNumber="366" pagination="245 - 247" refId="ref13222" refString="FAHR, J., B. A. DJOSSA, and H. VIERHAUS. 2006. Rapid assessment of bats (Chiroptera) in Dere, Diecke and Mt. Bero classified forests, southeastern Guinea; including a review of the distribution of bats in Guinee Forestiere. Pp. 168 - 180, 245 - 247, in A rapid biological assessment of three classified forests in Southeastern Guinea (H. E. WRIGHT, J. MCCULLOUGH, L. E. ALONSO, and M. S. DIALLO, eds.). Conservation International, RAP Bulletin of Biological Assessment, Washington, D. C., 40, 248 pp." type="book chapter" year="2006">
Fahr 
<emphasis box="[936,993,348,374]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="366">et al</emphasis>
., 2006
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="FAHR, J." box="[1100,1247,348,374]" pageId="7" pageNumber="366" pagination="336 - 337" refId="ref12611" refString="FAHR, J. 2013 b. Rhinolophus hillorum Upland horseshoe bat. Pp. 336 - 337, in The mammals of Africa. Volume IV: Hedgehogs, shrews and bats (M. HAPPOLD and D. C. D. HAPPOLD, eds.). Bloomsbury Publishing, London, 800 pp." type="book chapter" year="2013">
Fahr, 2013 
<emphasis box="[1232,1247,348,374]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="366">b</emphasis>
</bibRefCitation>
for details of these re-identifications). All specimens had round- ed connecting processes and forearms of 53.0– 
<quantity box="[809,914,450,476]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.49" pageId="7" pageNumber="366" unit="mm" value="54.9">54.9 mm</quantity>
(
<emphasis box="[932,947,450,476]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="366">n</emphasis>
= 5).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
